# ⛽ Gas Monitoring System Overview

The Gas Monitoring System serves as the primary environmental sensing subsystem responsible for detecting hazardous gas concentrations in industrial environments.

The system is designed to continuously monitor combustible and harmful gases using MQ-series gas sensors integrated with IoT-enabled communication modules for real-time data acquisition and wireless monitoring.

The framework enables rapid gas leakage detection, remote environmental observation, and continuous transmission of sensor data to centralized monitoring interfaces.

---

# ⚙️ Gas Monitoring Architecture

The gas monitoring architecture follows a linear sensing and communication pipeline consisting of:

- Gas Sensing Unit
- Data Processing Unit
- Wireless Communication Layer
- Real-Time Monitoring Interface

The system continuously acquires gas concentration data, processes sensor outputs, and transmits environmental information through wireless communication modules.

---

# 🧩 Core Components

## Gas Sensors

### MQ-2 Sensor
Used for detection of:
- LPG
- Smoke
- Hydrogen
- Methane

### MQ-5 Sensor
Used for detection of:
- LPG
- Natural Gas
- Methane
- Combustible gases

The sensors operate based on variations in electrical resistance corresponding to gas concentration levels.

---

## Processing Unit

### Arduino UNO
The Arduino UNO functions as the central processing unit responsible for:
- Reading analog sensor outputs
- Processing gas concentration data
- Performing analog-to-digital conversion
- Managing sensor communication workflows

---

## Wireless Communication Modules

### HC-05 Bluetooth Module
Enables:
- Short-range wireless communication
- Mobile device connectivity
- Real-time sensor observation through Bluetooth interfaces

### NodeMCU ESP8266
Provides:
- Wi-Fi-based communication
- IoT-enabled monitoring
- Wireless data transmission
- Remote dashboard integration

---

# 📡 Operational Workflow

The gas monitoring system operates through the following workflow:

## Step 1 — Gas Detection
MQ-series sensors continuously monitor surrounding environmental conditions.

## Step 2 — Sensor Data Acquisition
Gas concentration variations generate analog voltage outputs proportional to detected gas intensity.

## Step 3 — Data Processing
The Arduino UNO processes sensor outputs and converts them into interpretable gas concentration values.

## Step 4 — Wireless Transmission
Processed data is transmitted through:
- Bluetooth communication
- Wi-Fi communication
- IoT-based interfaces

## Step 5 — Monitoring & Visualization
Gas concentration readings are displayed on monitoring platforms for real-time observation and analysis.

